# fedora-to-endeavouros — migration primer
#
# moving from Fedora 44 to EndeavourOS. both are systemd-based, glibc-based,
# Wayland-by-default desktop linuxes. most of your muscle memory transfers
# directly. the real differences are:
#
#   1. PACKAGE MANAGER: dnf → pacman (see [[pacman]])
#   2. PACKAGE FORMAT:  rpm → pkg.tar.zst (see [[rpm]] vs pacman)
#   3. RELEASE MODEL:   point release (6mo) → true rolling
#   4. AUR:             new concept. user-submitted build recipes.
#   5. SELINUX:         enforcing by default → AppArmor optional, neither typical
#   6. FIREWALL:        firewalld → no firewall on by default (see [[ufw]])
#   7. CONFIG MERGE:    .rpmnew → .pacnew (different tool, same idea)
#   8. NEWS DISCIPLINE: nothing required → READ archlinux.org/news before -Syu
#
# this file walks the migration in order: capture state → install endeavour →
# port packages → restore configs → day-one setup → maintenance loop.


PRE-MIGRATION: CAPTURE YOUR FEDORA 44 STATE
-------------------------------------------

# do this BEFORE you touch the installer. without it, you'll spend a week
# remembering what you had installed and why.

# 1. snapshot the list of explicitly-installed packages (not deps).
#    this is the migration list.
dnf repoquery --userinstalled --queryformat '%{name}\n' \
    | sort -u > ~/fedora-userinstalled.txt

# 2. capture EVERY rpm currently installed (for cross-reference, not import)
rpm -qa --qf '%{NAME}\n' | sort -u > ~/fedora-all-rpms.txt

# 3. capture enabled repos + COPRs (you'll need analogous AUR pkgs)
dnf repolist enabled > ~/fedora-repos.txt
dnf copr list > ~/fedora-coprs.txt 2>/dev/null

# 4. capture flatpaks (these port directly — flatpak is cross-distro)
flatpak list --columns=application > ~/fedora-flatpaks.txt

# 5. capture enabled systemd units (your services / timers / sockets)
systemctl list-unit-files --state=enabled --no-pager > ~/fedora-enabled-units.txt
systemctl --user list-unit-files --state=enabled --no-pager \
    > ~/fedora-enabled-user-units.txt

# 6. dotfiles + ~/.config + ~/.local/share. if these aren't in git already,
#    now is when you regret it. minimum viable backup:
tar czf ~/fedora-dotfiles.tar.gz \
    --exclude='.cache' --exclude='.mozilla/firefox/*/Cache*' \
    -C ~ .bashrc .zshrc .profile .config .local .ssh .gnupg

# 7. browser profiles, password stores, gpg keys, ssh keys.
#    do not skip the GPG/SSH backup. losing these is the worst-case path.
cp -a ~/.gnupg ~/migration-backup/
cp -a ~/.ssh ~/migration-backup/

# 8. /etc — only the files YOU edited. easy filter: anything mtime-newer
#    than the package install. or just tar all of /etc and grep later.
sudo tar czf ~/fedora-etc.tar.gz -C / etc

# 9. /var/lib for services you run (postgres, mysql, docker volumes,
#    podman containers, etc). format-specific dumps are safer than
#    file-level copies:
sudo -u postgres pg_dumpall > ~/postgres-dump.sql
docker save -o ~/docker-images.tar $(docker images -q)

# stash all of this somewhere NOT on the disk you're about to wipe.
# external SSD, second internal drive, or rsync to another machine.


INSTALL ENDEAVOUROS
-------------------

# 1. grab the ISO from endeavouros.com (Galileo Neo or current release).
#    `dd` it to a USB (see [[dd]]).

# 2. boot the live USB. you get a small XFCE live env with a launcher
#    for the Calamares installer.

# 3. installer choices that matter:
#    - ONLINE install (lets you pick DE; offline is XFCE only).
#    - DESKTOP: pick what you had on fedora. KDE Plasma if you came from
#      Fedora KDE Spin; GNOME if from Workstation.
#    - FILESYSTEM: btrfs is strongly recommended for the snapshot story
#      (rolling-release safety net; see [[btrfs]] for the why).
#
#      *** GOTCHA: the filesystem dropdown is EASY TO MISS. ***
#      It is not its own screen. On the "Partitions" step, after you
#      pick "Erase disk", a small "File System" dropdown appears RIGHT
#      UNDER the radio button, defaulted to ext4. Change it to btrfs
#      THERE. There is no separate "choose filesystem" page. Most
#      people scan past it because the radio buttons grab the eye and
#      end up on ext4 by accident.
#
#      If you only notice after install: timeshift still works on ext4
#      (rsync mode), just slower and without bootable snapshots from
#      GRUB. While the install is still fresh, a reinstall is 15
#      minutes well spent. Do NOT try btrfs-convert on the live root —
#      it won't give you the @ / @home subvolume layout calamares
#      sets up, and timeshift-autosnap won't wire up cleanly.
#
#    - BOOTLOADER: systemd-boot if you're on plain EFI; grub if you
#      want bootable-snapshot integration (see [[btrfs]] + grub-btrfs).
#    - SWAP: pick "Swap (with Hibernate)" if you want a working
#      hibernate, or no-swap + zram (more common on modern systems).
#      On btrfs, this option creates a swap PARTITION (not a swapfile),
#      which sidesteps the chattr +C / nodatacow / no-compression dance
#      a hand-rolled btrfs swapfile needs (see [[btrfs]] GOTCHAS).
#    - PACKAGES: trim the desktop bundle, don't add yet. install
#      explicitly post-boot so you build a clean explicit-installed list.

# 4. post-install, the welcome app shows up. it has shortcuts for:
#    - update mirrors (rate-rank arch's mirrors for your region)
#    - update system
#    - install nvidia drivers (if applicable)
#    - common app-installer panels (steam, browsers, etc.)
#    run "Update mirrors" first, then "Update system", then close it.

# 5. enable timeshift + timeshift-autosnap BEFORE you do anything serious:
sudo pacman -S timeshift timeshift-autosnap
sudo timeshift --create --comments "post-install baseline" --tags D
# now every -Syu auto-snapshots first. see [[btrfs]] MANJARO + TIMESHIFT
# INTEGRATION — the same hook works on endeavour.


CALAMARES GOTCHAS — the easy-to-miss installer choices
------------------------------------------------------

# the filesystem dropdown (covered above) is the most-missed one. the
# rest, ranked roughly by how often they bite:
#
# 1. OFFLINE INSTALL IS XFCE ONLY. picking "offline" because it's faster
#    locks you into XFCE — there's no DE picker on the offline path. if
#    you want KDE / GNOME / Cinnamon / Budgie / anything else, you MUST
#    pick the ONLINE install.
#
# 2. DE SELECTION IS MULTI-SELECT (CHECKBOXES, NOT RADIO BUTTONS). you
#    can accidentally tick KDE + GNOME + XFCE and end up with three
#    login session options, three menu launchers' worth of duplicated
#    apps, and a 6 GB install. pick ONE unless you specifically want
#    a side-by-side. inversely: ticking nothing is valid (gives you a
#    bare WM like i3/bspwm/Qtile if those are also offered), but
#    surprises people who thought it meant "use the default".
#
# 3. "NO DESKTOP" OPTION EXISTS. literal terminal-only boot. people
#    click it thinking it means "default desktop". if you want a GUI,
#    don't pick this one.
#
# 4. BOOTLOADER: systemd-boot vs GRUB.
#    - GRUB is the default on most spins. KEEP IT if you want bootable
#      snapshots — `grub-btrfs` plugs into GRUB only; systemd-boot has
#      no equivalent for booting into a btrfs snapshot.
#    - systemd-boot is smaller / faster but UEFI-only. if your system
#      is legacy BIOS, systemd-boot won't even appear as an option.
#    - if you're dual-booting Windows, GRUB handles the os-prober
#      detection automatically.
#
# 5. LUKS ENCRYPTION CHECKBOX. it lives on the SAME partition screen as
#    the filesystem dropdown — small "Encrypt system" checkbox below
#    the layout choice. easy to accidentally enable, easier to miss if
#    you wanted it. the passphrase prompt comes up only if it's ticked.
#
# 6. NVIDIA LIVE-USB BOOT OPTION HAS TO BE PICKED *BEFORE* THE INSTALLER.
#    on the GRUB boot menu of the live USB there's a second entry like
#    "Start EndeavourOS with proprietary nvidia drivers". the installer
#    does NOT expose this — by the time calamares is open you've already
#    chosen. miss it on a hybrid laptop with a discrete nvidia GPU and
#    the live env is glitchy or won't reach the desktop. (you can still
#    install nvidia drivers post-install via the welcome app; the live
#    USB choice only affects the live environment itself.)
#
# 7. HOSTNAME DEFAULTS TO "endeavouros". set it to something
#    identifying ("$USER-laptop", "tower", whatever). two endeavouros
#    boxes on the same LAN with the same hostname is a small mess.
#
# 8. KEYBOARD LAYOUT VARIANT. auto-detect picks the base layout (US,
#    GB, DE, ...) but not the variant. US-International, US-Dvorak,
#    GB-extended, DE-neo etc. users should explicitly select the
#    variant from the dropdown — the test field at the bottom of the
#    screen is where you confirm `@`, `<>`, `~`, accented chars all
#    produce what you expect.
#
# 9. "AUTOMATICALLY LOG IN" CHECKBOX. convenience option on the user
#    setup screen. uncheck this on a laptop you carry out of the
#    house — a stolen powered-off laptop with auto-login is a stolen
#    laptop the thief can log in to.
#
# 10. PACKAGE BUNDLES SCREEN (online install). shows optional bundles
#     like firewall, printing (CUPS), accessibility, fonts, accessibility
#     tools, common laptop helpers. DEFAULTS ARE REASONABLE BUT READ
#     THEM ONCE. adding printer support or extra font sets later is
#     annoying compared to one checkbox now.
#
# 11. ERASE DISK vs REPLACE PARTITION vs MANUAL.
#     - "Erase disk" wipes the WHOLE selected disk. confirm the disk
#       picker at the top of the screen — if you have two SSDs plugged
#       in, picking the wrong one is data loss.
#     - "Replace partition" silently wipes whichever partition you
#       click on in the layout view. dual-booters: triple-check.
#     - "Manual" gives you full control + responsibility. for UEFI
#       systems you need an EFI System Partition (~512 MB, FAT32,
#       mounted at /boot or /boot/efi). missing it = unbootable.
#
# 12. TIMEZONE AUTO-DETECT USES IP GEOLOCATION. wrong if you're on a
#     VPN during install. fix from the map / dropdown on the timezone
#     screen, or post-install:
sudo timedatectl set-timezone America/Los_Angeles
#
# 13. SEPARATE /HOME PARTITION? if you want one, you have to use Manual
#     partitioning. "Erase disk" puts everything on one big partition
#     (or one btrfs with subvolumes, if you picked btrfs — which is
#     actually fine, since @home is its own snapshottable subvolume).
#     a separate /home PARTITION is mostly an old-habit thing now;
#     btrfs subvolumes get you the same isolation without the
#     pre-allocated-size trap.


PACKAGE MANAGER MAPPING — dnf → pacman
--------------------------------------

# the day-to-day commands. memorize this table. see [[pacman]] for depth.

#  fedora                              endeavour / arch
#  ---------------------------------   ---------------------------------
#  sudo dnf install foo                sudo pacman -S foo
#  sudo dnf remove foo                 sudo pacman -Rns foo
#  sudo dnf upgrade                    sudo pacman -Syu
#  sudo dnf upgrade --refresh          sudo pacman -Syyu
#  sudo dnf check-update               checkupdates           (from pacman-contrib)
#  dnf list installed                  pacman -Q
#  dnf list installed | grep foo       pacman -Qs foo
#  dnf info foo                        pacman -Si foo         (sync)
#                                      pacman -Qi foo         (installed)
#  dnf repoquery --userinstalled       pacman -Qe
#  dnf list --installed | grep ...     pacman -Qm             (NOT-in-repo: AUR / local)
#  dnf provides /usr/bin/foo           pacman -F /usr/bin/foo (after `pacman -Fy`)
#  rpm -qf /usr/bin/foo                pacman -Qo /usr/bin/foo
#  rpm -ql foo                         pacman -Ql foo
#  rpm -V foo                          pacman -Qkk foo
#  dnf clean all                       sudo pacman -Scc
#  dnf history                         /var/log/pacman.log
#  dnf autoremove                      sudo pacman -Rns $(pacman -Qdtq)
#  dnf swap A B                        sudo pacman -S B       (pacman auto-resolves)
#  dnf mark install foo                sudo pacman -D --asexplicit foo
#  dnf mark remove foo                 sudo pacman -D --asdeps foo
#  dnf copr enable user/proj           — closest analog: AUR (see below)
#  dnf module enable foo:stream        — no analog; arch ships one version per pkg
#  dnf needs-restarting                — closest: `needrestart` package, or reboot
#  dnf system-upgrade                  sudo pacman -Syu       (always; rolling)

# CRITICAL difference: NEVER run `pacman -Sy foo` (without -u). this
# refreshes the database without upgrading, then installs foo — which can
# pull in a fresh dependency against a stale system. always:
#     sudo pacman -Syu                      # upgrade first, then
#     sudo pacman -S foo                    # install
# this "partial upgrade" trap doesn't exist on dnf; it's the #1 way new
# arch users break their system.


PACKAGE NAME MAPPING — the common ones that differ
--------------------------------------------------

# most package names are the same. these are the gotchas:

#  fedora                              arch / endeavour
#  ---------------------------------   ---------------------------------
#  @development-tools                  base-devel              (group)
#  @virtualization                     qemu-full libvirt virt-manager
#  kernel-headers                      linux-headers
#  kernel-devel                        linux-headers
#  glibc-langpack-en                   — locales handled via /etc/locale.gen
#  pulseaudio-utils                    pulseaudio              (or pipewire-pulse)
#  pipewire-pulseaudio                 pipewire-pulse
#  NetworkManager-tui                  networkmanager          (nmtui is in there)
#  policycoreutils-python-utils        — selinux not standard on arch
#  setools-console                     — selinux not standard on arch
#  java-21-openjdk                     jdk-openjdk             (latest is default)
#  java-21-openjdk-devel               jdk-openjdk             (-devel is bundled)
#  python3                             python                  (python IS python 3)
#  python3-pip                         python-pip
#  python3-virtualenv                  python-virtualenv
#  nodejs-npm                          npm
#  golang                              go
#  ImageMagick                         imagemagick             (lowercase)
#  ffmpeg-free                         ffmpeg                  (full ffmpeg shipped)
#  vlc                                 vlc
#  google-chrome-stable                google-chrome           (AUR)
#  code                                code                    (open source build)
#                                      visual-studio-code-bin  (microsoft build, AUR)
#  zoom                                zoom                    (AUR)
#  slack                               slack-desktop           (AUR)
#  1password                           1password               (AUR)
#  spotify-client                      spotify                 (AUR)
#  steam                               steam                   (needs multilib repo)
#  podman-docker                       podman                  (docker alias separate)
#  podman-compose                      podman-compose

# the "needs multilib" point: steam, wine, lutris and friends need 32-bit
# libs. enable multilib in /etc/pacman.conf — uncomment [multilib] and the
# Include line — then `sudo pacman -Syu`. see [[pacman]] PACMAN.CONF.


COPR → AUR — the closest analog
-------------------------------

# fedora's COPR (community packages built on koji) is roughly the AUR's
# equivalent on the rpm side. the differences:
#
#   - COPR ships built binaries from a trusted-ish builder.
#   - AUR ships build RECIPES (PKGBUILDs); your machine builds them.
#   - both are community-maintained, unreviewed, "trust the maintainer".
#
# yay is preinstalled on endeavour. usage:
yay -Ss foo                            # search repos + AUR
yay -Si foo                            # info on an AUR package
yay -S foo                             # install (builds + installs)
yay -Syu                               # upgrade everything (repos + AUR)
yay -Yc                                # clean orphaned AUR build dirs

# the "binary cache for popular AUR" equivalent is chaotic-aur (third-party
# repo). garuda uses it by default; endeavour doesn't. if you want
# google-chrome / spotify / discord without compiling, the -bin variants
# (e.g. spotify, google-chrome) are already prebuilt by their AUR
# maintainers — no chaotic-aur needed.


FLATPAK — same on both sides
----------------------------

# flatpak is identical between fedora and endeavour. your flatpak app list
# ports unchanged. on endeavour:
sudo pacman -S flatpak
flatpak remote-add --if-not-exists flathub \
    https://flathub.org/repo/flathub.flatpakrepo
flatpak install flathub org.mozilla.firefox      # for example

# bulk-restore from the fedora capture:
while read app; do flatpak install -y flathub "$app"; done < ~/fedora-flatpaks.txt

# the integration point that differs: fedora preconfigures the
# fedora-flatpaks remote with rebuilt-by-redhat versions. on arch you only
# have flathub by default. for most users that's fine.


SERVICES & SYSTEMD — mostly the same
------------------------------------

# both are systemd. same commands, same unit files, same enable/start/status.
systemctl enable --now sshd            # same syntax
journalctl -u sshd --since today       # same syntax

# the things that differ:
#
# - SELINUX: fedora ships enforcing; arch ships nothing. don't enable
#   selinux on arch — the package set isn't labeled and you'll be in
#   a maze of avc denials. if you want MAC, use AppArmor (`pacman -S
#   apparmor`), which has working profiles for common services.
#
# - FIREWALLD: not default on arch. install + enable manually if you
#   want it, or use ufw (see [[ufw]]):
sudo pacman -S firewalld
sudo systemctl enable --now firewalld
#   or
sudo pacman -S ufw
sudo systemctl enable --now ufw
sudo ufw default deny incoming
sudo ufw enable
#
# - JOURNALD STORAGE: defaults to /var/log/journal on both. fedora caps
#   more aggressively. tune Journal{,Storage}MaxUse= in
#   /etc/systemd/journald.conf if you find logs ballooning.


DAY-ONE INSTALL CHECKLIST
-------------------------

# the post-install ritual. run in this order.

# 1. mirror rank + first full update
sudo pacman -S reflector
sudo reflector --country US --age 12 --sort rate --save /etc/pacman.d/mirrorlist
sudo pacman -Syu

# 2. dev toolchain bootstrap (same group as fedora's @development-tools)
sudo pacman -S --needed base-devel git
sudo pacman -S --needed neovim vim tmux zsh

# 3. languages you actually use (skip what you don't)
sudo pacman -S --needed python python-pip rustup nodejs npm go clang cmake ninja
rustup default stable                     # if you grabbed rustup

# 4. CLI you'll miss from fedora (most are 1:1 named):
sudo pacman -S --needed ripgrep fd bat fzf jq htop wget curl unzip

# 5. desktop apps (pick what you used). repos cover most;
#    AUR for proprietary (chrome, vscode-ms, zoom, slack, 1password):
sudo pacman -S firefox thunderbird libreoffice-fresh gimp inkscape vlc keepassxc

# 6. containers / VMs
sudo pacman -S docker docker-compose
# or
sudo pacman -S podman podman-compose
sudo systemctl enable --now docker         # only if you chose docker

sudo pacman -S qemu-full libvirt virt-manager
sudo systemctl enable --now libvirtd
sudo usermod -aG libvirt "$USER"

# 7. multilib (steam, wine, 32-bit libs). edit /etc/pacman.conf,
#    uncomment [multilib] + its Include line, then:
sudo pacman -Syu
sudo pacman -S steam wine-staging lutris

# 8. nvidia (skip if intel/amd):
sudo pacman -S nvidia nvidia-utils nvidia-settings
#    (the endeavour welcome app has a button that does this and the
#    kernel-param plumbing for you — preferred.)

# 9. enable the firewall of your choice (see SERVICES above).

# 10. fonts. fedora's font stack is more curated than arch's defaults:
sudo pacman -S ttf-liberation ttf-dejavu noto-fonts noto-fonts-emoji \
    ttf-cascadia-code ttf-jetbrains-mono ttf-fira-code

# 11. set the hostname / timezone if installer didn't:
sudo hostnamectl set-hostname mybox
sudo timedatectl set-timezone America/Los_Angeles

# 12. restore dotfiles:
cd ~ && tar xzf ~/migration-backup/fedora-dotfiles.tar.gz
chmod 700 ~/.ssh ~/.gnupg
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/id_* 2>/dev/null

# 13. set up timeshift (see INSTALL section). create a baseline snapshot:
sudo pacman -S timeshift timeshift-autosnap
sudo timeshift --create --comments "post-day-one-setup" --tags D


PORTING YOUR FEDORA PACKAGE LIST
--------------------------------

# DO NOT pipe ~/fedora-userinstalled.txt straight into `pacman -S`. names
# differ enough that you'll get partial failures and pull in stuff you
# never asked for.

# the disciplined approach: walk the list manually, install in groups,
# accept that some fedora packages don't exist on arch (selinux tooling,
# fedora-flatpaks-only apps, kernel-modules-extra bits).

# the lazy approach: use `pacman -Ss` per name to check, then install
# in batches:
for pkg in $(cat ~/fedora-userinstalled.txt); do
    pacman -Ss "^${pkg}$" >/dev/null 2>&1 && echo "$pkg" || echo "MISSING: $pkg"
done > ~/port-status.txt
grep -v MISSING ~/port-status.txt | xargs -r sudo pacman -S --needed --noconfirm
grep MISSING ~/port-status.txt        # the manual-fix list

# for the MISSING list: try the same name on AUR (`yay -Ss <name>`), or
# look up the upstream project name and search both.


CONFIG MERGE — .pacnew vs .rpmnew (same idea, different prefix)
---------------------------------------------------------------

# fedora's .rpmnew / .rpmsave files have direct equivalents:
#   .pacnew  — package shipped a new version, your edited file was kept
#   .pacsave — package was removed, your edited file was preserved
#
# every big -Syu drops some of these. merging them is part of the
# maintenance loop. use pacdiff (interactive 3-way diff):
sudo pacman -S pacman-contrib
sudo pacdiff
sudo find /etc -name '*.pacnew' -o -name '*.pacsave'


THE MAINTENANCE LOOP — what changes from fedora
-----------------------------------------------

# fedora cadence:
#   - dnf upgrade weekly-ish
#   - dnf system-upgrade every 6 months for the release bump
#   - that's it
#
# endeavour cadence:
#   - check archlinux.org/news once a week (RSS-friendly)
#   - sudo pacman -Syu weekly-ish
#   - merge .pacnew files after each big update
#   - keep an eye on /var/log/pacman.log for `[ALPM]` warnings
#   - if you go >1 month without updating, refresh the keyring FIRST:
sudo pacman -Sy archlinux-keyring && sudo pacman -Syu
#   - never run partial upgrades: never `pacman -Sy <foo>` without `-u`

# the news discipline matters. manual-intervention notices (e.g. "this
# pacman upgrade requires you to remove /etc/pacman.d/mirrorlist.pacnew
# first") live there and nowhere else. miss one and you can break boot.


THINGS YOU'LL MISS / NEW HABITS
-------------------------------

# 1. dnf history rollback — pacman has no equivalent. timeshift is the
#    replacement: snapshot before, roll back the WHOLE system if needed.
#    individual package downgrade is `pacman -U /var/cache/pacman/pkg/<old>`
#    (see [[pacman]] DOWNGRADING).
#
# 2. dnf modules / streams — gone. arch ships exactly one version of each
#    package. for old-version needs: AUR `-lts` / `-legacy` variants,
#    or a container/toolbx-equivalent.
#
# 3. needs-restarting — install the `needrestart` package, or just
#    reboot after kernel / glibc / systemd / dbus updates.
#
# 4. SELinux — gone by default. don't try to bring it back; the
#    package set isn't labeled. use AppArmor if you need MAC.
#
# 5. firewalld zones — install firewalld if you liked them; ufw is
#    simpler (see [[ufw]]).
#
# 6. fedora's curated kernel — arch's linux package is vanilla-ish.
#    if you want LTS stability, `pacman -S linux-lts` and keep both
#    installed. zen kernel for desktop responsiveness. you can boot
#    either from grub / systemd-boot.
#
# 7. dnf groups — pacman GROUPS exist but are shallower. base-devel is
#    the main one you'll use. fedora's @workstation-product, etc., have
#    no direct analog — endeavour's installer is where group-like
#    decisions get made.
#
# 8. SECURITY UPDATES on a schedule — pacman doesn't categorize updates
#    as security vs feature. you upgrade everything. this is the rolling-
#    release trade: smaller deltas more often, no separate security stream.


WHAT YOU CAN LEAVE BEHIND
-------------------------

# - dnf-specific tooling: dnf-plugins-core, dnf-automatic, etc.
# - SELinux policy authoring tooling.
# - firewalld unless you actively want it.
# - rpm-build / mock / koji bits.
# - fedora-packager, fedora-easy-karma, fedora-review.
# - Anaconda/Kickstart files (calamares replaces this).


ROLLBACK PLAN — if endeavour doesn't stick
------------------------------------------

# the backups you took (PRE-MIGRATION section) are also your rollback path.
# reinstall fedora 44 from media, restore /etc, /home, /var/lib service
# state. this is why we tar'd /etc and dumped postgres rather than relying
# on filesystem copies.
#
# if you go btrfs on endeavour and keep send/receive backups (see [[btrfs]]
# SEND / RECEIVE), the same snapshots work as a per-system backup.


